Unchanged Impact to our thesis
Modest upside Financial results versus consensus
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

NTNX's FQ4 played out mostly as expected, with top- line Street estimates largely staying as is, which we indicated would create a little weakness that we would be buyers of. Opportunity for share gains and leverage keep us buyers of the name, despite some volatility in ARR growth / NRR.
NTNX FQ4 played out largely as expected, outperforming on top- line and margins.
While the 2,700+ new customers in FY25 is encouraging, ARR and NRR in FQ4 decelerated to 17% Y/Y / 108% from 18% / 110% last quarter.
Initial Dell PowerFlex wins in the quarter, including two Global 2000 customers encouraging.
Pure PowerFlex remains on track to be available at the end of the calendar.
With a long pipeline left in the VMware opportunity, we would be buyers of weakness.

Seeing evidence of share gain thesis. We have continued to favor NTNX for the opportunity to gain share from VMW in coming years. We are starting to see this thesis play out, with company adding 2,700+ customers during the year (35%+ for new customer growth), and new customers for standalone hypervisor / Dell PowerFlex including two Fortune 2000 companies. We see this standalone hypervisor as an important way to get new, larger customers onboard. ARR deceleration to 17% from 18% and NRR dropping to 108% from 110% will limit follow- though on a better than expected guide, and something we will monitor, but note restatement of these metrics to account for deferred licenses make decks not look as oncerning. As a result of what we see as a long pipeline for NTNX, we would be buyers of weakness, particularly as company continues to exceed profitability guidance.

Upside on top- line and margins, although ARR growth and NRR decelerate. NTNX reported FQ4 non- GAAP revenue / EPS of \(\) 653\(mm /\) \ \(0.37\) , vs. our expectations for \(\) 640.1\(mm /\) \ \(0.26\) . Revenue was driven by strength in new customers, with 2,700+ new customers during FY25. NRR was 108%, decelerating from 110% last quarter. The company continues to see more variability with US Federal. Management noted that the majority of the VMware opportunity still to come, with management seeing

the company in the 2nd inning of the opportunity. Initial Dell PowerFlex wins in the quarter, with interest from large customers including two Global 2000 customers. Pure PowerFlex remains on track to be available at the end of the calendar year. ARR came in at \(\sim \$ 2.223bn\) , growing \(+17\%\) Y/Y (decelerating from \(+18\%\) last quarter). On both NRR and ARR deceleration, the company noted timing changes that could impact these metrics, particularly around deferrals, which with back dating made deceleration not appear as big. Non- GAAP gross margins came in at \(88.3\%\) (vs. MSe of \(86.6\%\) ) and non- GAAP operating margin came in at \(18.3\%\) (vs. MSe of \(12.3\%\) ), benefitting from higher revenue and lower operating expenses. Free cash flow came in at \(\) 207.8\(mm. Stronger revenue led to an EPS beat of\) \ \(0.37\) vs. MSe of \(\) 0.26\(.\) \ \(50mm\) of stock under existing share repurchase authorization. Board has approved \(\) 350mm\(increase to existing share repurchase authorization.\)

Lower FQ1 top- line but FY26 remains largely the same. Our FY26 top- line remains largely the same, although we lower FQ1 top- line to account for continued uncertainty in macro with US Fed, typically a seasonally strong US Federal quarter. We increase operating expenses to account for delayed hiring impacting operating expenses. We would note a ACV cohort available to renew in FY26 is growing over 25, but at a slower pace than 25. Our new FQ4 / FY25 non- GAAP revenue / EPS estimates are now \(\) 675.1mm\(/\) \ \(0.41\) and \(\) 2,920.0mm\(/\) \ \(1.87\) from \(\) 685.9mm\(/\) \ \(0.46\) and \(\) 2,915.2mm\(/\) \ \(1.79\) previously.

Remain OW, \(\) 90\(PT. Our\) \ \(90\) base case is 32x street CY26e FCF of \(\) 830mm\(. Our multiple of 32x is in - line with the software universe growing FCF\) \sim 30\% \(. Our bear case is\) \ \(52\) , \(20x \sim\) 750 mm CY26e FCF. The multiple 20x is more in- line with the lower end of software multiples and the bottom end of NTNX's historical trading range. Our bull case is \(\) 110\(, 36x \sim\) 900 mm CY26e FCF. The multiple 36x is more in- line with software names growing FCF \(30\% +\) . Risks to our PT include changes in tariffs impact server demand, macro weakness softens spending, share gains from VMware prove difficult.

Nutanix should be able to capture share from VMware's business, with Dell/Cisco partnerships and channel/architectural changes helping to accelerate the opportunity, creating a path towards strong cash flow generation and achievability of long term FCF targets.

Upside to FY25/FY27 targets from analyst day. More meaningful share gains from VMware driven by expansion of partnerships and successful product releases (e.g. standalone hypervisor). Able to see greater revenue contribution from non- HCI pieces of platform. Our bull case assumes more strategic activity in the space. Trade at closer to average historical trading range (CY26 FCF of \(\) 900\mathrm{mm}\$ ).

Long term targets achievable (upside to FY25/FY27 FCF targets). Nutanix trades in line with software multiples growing FCF \(\sim 30\%\) . VMW share gains more meaningful in FY25 vs. FY24, with acceleration potential with Cisco/Dell partnerships and channel/architecture changes.

Meaningfully slower spend environment given macro/tariffs stunts ability to reach Analyst Day targets. Macro weakens as tariffs meaningfully pressure spending environment and share gains from VMware proves difficult. CY26 FCF of \(\sim\) 750mm. Trade at lower end of software multiple and the bottom end of NTNX's historical trading range.
